:"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England","Lincoln, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1290–15 September 1332":"1290–15 September 1332","1290–1332":"1290–1332","1290–1312":"1290–1312","–Female":"Deceased","1312–1391":"1312–1391","1302–1346":"1302–1346","1265–Male":"1265–Deceased","1264–Female":"1264–Deceased","about 1280":"about 1280","1264":"1264","1391":"1391","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","15 September 1332":"15 September 1332","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","Abt 1310":"about 1310","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","about 1312":"about 1312","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Ingoldsby, Kesteven, Lincolnshire, England, UK":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Escrick, Yorkshire, England":"Escrick, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England","Lincoln, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dawnay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from one of the many places in northern France named from an alder grove (Old French  <i>aulnai</i>,  <i>aulnoi</i>, latinized as  <i>alnetum</i>), such as Annay (Pas-de-Calais), Aulnay (Aube, Marne, Calvados), Aulnois (Aisne), and Aunay (Calvados, Eure-et-Loire, Seine-et-Oise). With fused preposition, Anglo-Norman French  <i>d'Aunai</i> became  <i>Dawnay</i>,  <i>Dawney</i> and (with loss of the final syllable)  <i>Dawn</i>.   Laney   is another form of this surname with fused definite article.  See also  Dando  , from Anglo-Norman French  <i>d'Aunou</i>, with which  <i>d'Aunai</i> may sometimes have been confused."],"variants":[{"name":"Dawney","meanings":["Norman, English:  See  Dawnay  ."]},{"name":"Laney","meanings":["Irish: probably a shortened and altered form of   McElhinney  .","English and Irish: habitational name introduced by the Normans originally deriving from any of the many places in northern France called L'Aunai (from Latin <i>alnetum</i> ‘alder grove’). It may also have developed to   Delaney  .","Variant of   Laine   2, a surname of French origin."]},{"name":"Dawn","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire): of Norman origin, probably a clipped form of <b>Dawnay</b> or <b>Dawney</b> (compare   Dana  ), habitational names from one of the many places in northern France named for an alder grove (Old French <i>aulnai</i>, <i>aulnoi</i>, Latinized as <i>alnetum</i>). With fused preposition <i>d(e)</i>, Anglo-Norman <i>d'Aunai</i> became <i>Dawnay</i>, <i>Dawney</i> and (with loss of the final syllable) <i>Dawn</i>.   Laney   is another form of this surname with fused definite article. See also   Dando  , from Anglo-Norman <i>d'Aunou</i>, with which <i>d'Aunai</i> may sometimes have been confused.","English: from Middle English <i>Dawen</i>, a variant of   Dawes   with the weak declension genitival suffix <i>-(e)n</i> (Old English <i>-an</i>) instead of the standard Middle English <i>-es</i>. The usage is mainly restricted to West Midlands dialects of Middle English.","Americanized form of German   Daun  ."]},{"name":"Doney","meanings":["English (Cornwall): of uncertain origin. There is a Richard <i>Donowe</i> recorded in 1451-64 as a tenant in Manuels, Saint Columb Minor, whose surname appears to be a pet form of an unidentified personal name with the Cornish hypocoristic suffix <i>-ow</i>. Formally this might have become <i>Doney</i> but <i>Donowe</i> itself seems not to have survived, unless it was altered to   Downey  . However, there is no evidence to suggest any connection of this west Cornwall surname with <i>Doney</i> in central and east Cornwall (Bodmin and Quethiock). Alternatively, perhaps it is a variant of the Devon name   Downey  , and with the main vowel shortened and lowered, but evidence for this is lacking.","Americanized form of French Canadian   Daunais   or   Donais  ."]},{"name":"Dando","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from Aunou-le-Faucon in Orne, Normandy, with fused preposition. Aunou was named for an alder grove, from Latin <i>alnus</i> ‘alder’ + the Gaulish suffix <i>-avum</i>. In medieval England <i>d'Aunou</i> developed an intrusive <i>-d-</i>, giving <i>Dando</i>. The surname was sometimes confused with <i>d'Aunay</i> or <i>d'Auney</i> (see   Delaney  )."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":38,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Dawnay was born in 1290, in Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Edmund Dawnay, was 26 and his mother, Frances Corminers, was 27. He married Elizabeth about 1310, in Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 15 September 1332, in England, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1290–15 September 1332":"1290–15. september 1332","1290–1332":"1290–1332","1290–1312":"1290–1312","–Female":"Surnud","1312–1391":"1312–1391","1302–1346":"1302–1346","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1264–Female":"1264–Surnud","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1264":"1264","1391":"1391","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","15 September 1332":"15. september 1332","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","Abt 1310":"umbes 1310","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","about 1312":"umbes 1312","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Ingoldsby, Kesteven, Lincolnshire, England, UK":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Escrick, Yorkshire, England":"Escrick, Yorkshire East Riding, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England","Lincoln, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1290–15 September 1332":"1290–15. syyskuuta 1332","1290–1332":"1290–1332","1290–1312":"1290–1312","–Female":"Kuollut","1312–1391":"1312–1391","1302–1346":"1302–1346","1265–Male